All vhosts are defined in a single file: `/home/ssm-user/apps/reverse-proxy/nginx/conf.d/default.conf`.

| Domain | Container chain | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `wcma.work` | reverse-proxy → `mapnj2:3001` | Next.js app; `general` rate limit. |
| `xyz.wcma.work` | reverse-proxy → `xyz:3002` | Next.js XYZ tile server (no rate limit). |
| `parcels.wcma.work` | reverse-proxy → `qgis-server:80` | Hard-pinned `MAP=/var/www/qgis_projects/wimmera_parcels/wimmera_parcels.qgz`; non-matching `MAP` returns `403`. |
| `wfml.wcma.work` | reverse-proxy → `qgis-server:80` (`/ows/`) + `lizmap-nginx:80` (`/`) | Lizmap front; `MAP` whitelisted to `^/var/www/qgis_projects/wfml/`. |
| `pozi.wcma.work` | reverse-proxy → `qgis-server:80` | WMS endpoint at `/ows/?MAP=/var/www/qgis_projects/pozi_base/pozi_base.qgs`. **This is what the Flutter app talks to.** Hard-pinned via `if ($arg_MAP != "..."){ return 403; }`. |

## QGIS Server container internals

- Image: official `qgis/qgis-server:ltr`
- Entrypoint: `/usr/local/bin/start-xvfb-nginx.sh`
  - Starts Xvfb (`:99`, screen 0, 1280x1024x16, +GLX +render)
  - Starts `spawn-fcgi` to launch `qgis_mapserv.fcgi` listening on `127.0.0.1:9993` (single FCGI process by default)
  - Starts internal nginx (master + 2 workers) listening on container port 80
- FCGI binary inside container: `/usr/lib/cgi-bin/qgis_mapserv.fcgi` (runs as `www-data`)
- Internal nginx config (host: `/home/ssm-user/apps/qgis-server/nginx/nginx.conf`) routes:
  - `/ows/...`  →  `rewrite /qgis/qgis_mapserv.fcgi`  →  `fastcgi_pass localhost:9993`
  - `/ogc/<repo>/`  →  `rewrite /qgis/qgis_mapserv.fcgi?map=/io/data/<repo>/<repo>.qgs`
  - `/wfs3/...`  →  `rewrite /qgis/qgis_mapserv.fcgi`
- FastCGI params include `SCRIPT_FILENAME`, `QUERY_STRING`, plus computed `HTTPS`, `SERVER_NAME`, `SERVER_PORT` derived from `X-Forwarded-*` headers (so the reverse-proxy must pass those).

### QGIS Server env vars (live)

```
QGIS_PREFIX_PATH=/usr
QGIS_PLUGINPATH=/opt/qgis-server/plugins
QGIS_AUTH_DB_DIR_PATH=/tmp/
QGIS_SERVER_PARALLEL_RENDERING=true
QGIS_SERVER_MAX_THREADS=2
QGIS_SERVER_LOG_LEVEL=2
QGIS_SERVER_LOG_STDERR=true
QGIS_SERVER_LIZMAP_REVEAL_SETTINGS=true
HOME=/var/lib/qgis
```

- Only **one** `qgis_mapserv.fcgi` process runs by default — but it does parallel rendering with up to `QGIS_SERVER_MAX_THREADS` threads. Increasing throughput requires either bumping FCGI process count (extra `spawn-fcgi -F N` flag) or raising `QGIS_SERVER_MAX_THREADS`. Note: per-tile multi-layer requests serialize on a single FCGI worker.
- The qgis-server container also exposes port 9993 (the FCGI socket) but that's an internal artefact of the image; only port 80 is consumed by the reverse-proxy.

## Reverse-proxy nginx — rate limiting

Three `limit_req` zones are **defined** in `/home/ssm-user/apps/reverse-proxy/nginx/nginx.conf`:

```nginx
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=general:10m rate=60r/s;
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=qgis:10m    rate=20r/m;   # ← typo for r/s — too tight for WMS clients
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=tiles:10m   rate=30r/s;   # ← defined but not applied to any vhost
```

**Status (2026-04-29): all `limit_req zone=qgis ...` directives are commented out** in `conf.d/default.conf` (lines 38, 58, 87, 156, 180, 213 — `parcels`, `wfml`, `pozi` `/ows/` blocks for both :80 and :443). This was the cause of `HTTP 503` from the Flutter app (`limiting requests, excess: X.X by zone "qgis", server: pozi.wcma.work` in the reverse-proxy error log). With the directives disabled, 30-parallel-request hammer tests now return 30/30 `200`.

Backup before edit: `/home/ssm-user/apps/reverse-proxy/nginx/conf.d/default.conf.bak.20260429` (root-owned).

When/if rate-limiting is re-introduced for `pozi.wcma.work`, target `rate=15r/s burst=60 nodelay` (or move it to the existing `tiles` zone). The `general` zone (`60r/s burst=100 nodelay`) and the `parcels.wcma.work` `cgi-bin` location remain unchanged otherwise.

The conf.d directory and `nginx.conf` are owned by `ssm-user`; reading from the `ubuntu` SSH user requires `sudo`.

## SSL / TLS

- All `:443` listeners use HTTP/2 and a single Let's Encrypt cert: `/etc/letsencrypt/live/wcma.work-0001/fullchain.pem` (+ `privkey.pem`). It's a SAN cert covering all four `*.wcma.work` vhosts.
- `:80 default_server` returns `444` (drop) for unknown hosts.
- ACME webroot mounted at `/home/ssm-user/apps/reverse-proxy/certbot/www/` (host) → standard Certbot HTTP-01 flow inside the reverse-proxy container.
- Pure TLS termination — does not influence upstream `4xx`/`5xx`.

## Observed quirks

- QGIS Server logs many `QFont::fromString: Invalid description '(empty)'` warnings — cosmetic, can be ignored.
- Some `GetMap` requests with the full default-on layer set return HTTP 400 (`270`-byte body) intermittently — likely a single layer in the project being temporarily unavailable. Investigate per-layer with isolated requests if it recurs.
- The qgis-server's internal nginx access log shows the **reverse-proxy's** internal Docker IP as the client (e.g. `172.19.0.5`), not the real user IP, because the reverse-proxy isn't passing through `X-Forwarded-For` to the access log format used inside the container.

## Operational notes

- No QGIS-related systemd unit on the host — everything is container-managed.
- No Apache on host — earlier `qgis_mapserv.fcgi` PIDs visible to `ps` are inside the `qgis-server` container, surfaced because Docker shares the host PID namespace via `ps`.
- No host nginx — the only nginx instances are inside containers (`nginx-reverse-proxy`, `qgis-server`, `lizmap-nginx`).
- Login user is `ubuntu`; everything in `/home/ssm-user/apps/` is owned by the `ssm-user` account (the SSM Session Manager default user). Use `sudo` to read those files when SSHed as `ubuntu`.

## Client expectations (Flutter app)

Pinned here so any server-side change keeps these in mind:

- Tile size: **512×512 PNG** (`WIDTH=512&HEIGHT=512`). One screen of map ≈ 4–9 tiles instead of 16–25.
- Concurrency: **2 in-flight WMS requests** per device (client-side `Pool`).
- Retry policy: 4 attempts on `{429, 502, 503, 504}` with jittered backoffs `~800ms / 2s / 4.5s` (±25%).
- Tile cache: persistent on-device disk cache; failed fetch falls back to last-good cached tile when available.
- WMS `MAP` parameter must contain a literal `/` (the app deliberately un-encodes `%2F` after `Uri.encodeQueryComponent`). The reverse-proxy / WAF must not block paths or query strings containing `/`.

So a sustainable rate-limit budget for one user moving the map should comfortably fit inside e.g. **`rate=15r/s burst=60 nodelay`** on the `qgis` zone.
